attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, not stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity MEDIUM because it was considered trojan.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a sophisticated DDoS botnet agent, likely a variant of the Gafgyt or Mirai families, targeting MIPSEL-based IoT devices. It features an extensive suite of DDoS attack vectors including HTTP, SYN, TCP, UDP, GRE, and RakNet floods. Concrete malicious behaviors include: 1) A 'killer' module that scans the /proc filesystem to identify and terminate competing malware processes; 2) Stealth techniques using the 'mount' syscall to hide its process directory in /proc; 3) System information exfiltration (uname, architecture, and current path) via the 'client_system' function; and 4) Use of modern cryptographic primitives (X25519 key exchange, ChaCha20-Poly1305 AEAD, and XXTEA) to secure Command and Control (C2) communications and obfuscate internal strings. Relevant IOCs include the hardcoded C2 IP logic in 'cnc_resolve' (0x9f60ea54) and specific HTTP flood templates targeting host 'target'.
